# Claude Code Instructions For {{REPO_NAME}}

This repository uses a file-based Claude Code and Codex collaboration protocol.
The workflow is part of the product: preserve shared state in repo files, keep
handoffs cold-readable, and stop at explicit approval gates.

## Required Reading

Before making changes, read:

- `{{PROTOCOL_PATH}}`
- `{{COLLAB_PATH}}`
- `{{PROJECT_BRIEF_PATH}}`
- `{{BROWSER_RUNNER_DOC_PATH_OR_NA}}`
- the latest file in `{{TURN_LOG_DIR}}`

If a listed path is `N/A`, record why in the turn note Evidence Basis.

## Accepted Operating Defaults

- Work local-first, not local-only: repo-file coordination is the default, and
  bridges/adapters are opt-in later layers only when Sami approves exact setup.
- Treat file-based handoff as the minimal binding reference: manual paste plus
  `COLLAB.md` and turn notes now, inbox/outbox files only if scoped.
- Treat signed event governance as an optional add-on unless the current
  authorization names it; do not edit trust/event files or create keys outside
  scope.
- Keep live bridges/adapters disabled: no MCP registration, plugin setup,
  `.mcp.json`, bridge enablement, or global config changes without approval.
- Respect the current experiment's authorized turn cap. Turn caps are
  per-experiment authorization values, not static repo-wide defaults.
- Browser QA must name the runner or explicitly say `N/A` with a reason.
- Automation budget is `N/A` unless polling, cron, webhook, or heartbeat work
  is explicitly approved.
- Council, GPT, Claude, and Codex consultation is optional and file-based by
  default through prompts, responses, digests, and turn notes.
- Treat gstack, AgentBridge, tmux bridges, LLM Council, Zenith, CCB, Claude
  Squad, and related projects as prior art only unless a separate scope
  approves dependency use.
- Kit extraction into another repository is a separate action; do not copy
  kit files into another repo without explicit approval.

## Collaboration Rules

- Treat `{{COLLAB_PATH}}` as the shared source of truth for current state.
- Add one append-only turn note under `{{TURN_LOG_DIR}}` for meaningful
  architecture, implementation, critique, smoke, portability, or handoff turns.
- Do not edit another agent's existing turn note except to fix a typo you made
  in the same turn.
- Do not assume Codex has seen hidden Claude context. Write decisions and
  constraints into repo files.
- When handing work to Codex, update `Next Request To Codex` in
  `{{COLLAB_PATH}}`. If the template includes a latest-response field, update
  `Latest Claude Response` as well.
- When answering Codex, update `Next Request To Codex` and, if present,
  `Latest Claude Response` in `{{COLLAB_PATH}}`.
- Stop at the turn cap named by the current experiment authorization unless
  Sami explicitly approves continuation.

## Safety Rules

- Do not install dependencies unless Sami explicitly approves it.
- Do not commit, push, merge, open a PR, or create a branch unless Sami
  explicitly asks.
- Do not use dangerous sandbox or approval-bypass modes.
- Do not delete files outside this repo.
- Do not modify global Claude/Codex config.
- Do not register MCP, set up plugins, enable bridges, or edit `.mcp.json`
  without exact approval.
- Do not edit signed trust/event/private-key files unless the current
  authorization names those files.
- Keep edits inside the authorized file list and record any blocker before
  expanding scope.

## Suggested Claude Role

Default to the product/architecture counterparty role:

- propose thin architecture,
- keep the user-facing app or workflow usable,
- ask Codex for critique before broad implementation,
- incorporate Codex feedback into repo-visible decisions.

## Browser Runner

Configured runner: `{{BROWSER_RUNNER_CHOICE}}`

Use the named runner for browser validation. If browser QA is not applicable,
write:

```text
Tool used: N/A
Reason: {{BROWSER_RUNNER_NA_REASON}}
```

If the named runner cannot communicate with the browser or target, stop and
report the connector/tool state instead of silently switching to another
browser automation stack.

When browser QA is needed, record concrete evidence in the turn note:

- URL or file path opened,
- action performed,
- visible outcome,
- console/network failure observed through the named runner.
